# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1990-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 22 November to 1 December 1962.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Athletic events were held at Perry Lakes Stadium in the suburb of Floreat and swimming events at Beatty Park in North Perth.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was held after the 1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Most venues other than the specifically constructed Lake Monger Velodrome, Beatty Park, and Perry Lakes Stadium, were existing facilities.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 35 teams were represented at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Note: The medals used at these Games were the first to have a neck chain.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] All previous games had their medals in presentation boxes.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The **1990 Commonwealth Games** (Māori: *1990 Taumāhekeheke Commonwealth*) were held in Auckland, New Zealand from, 24 January – 3 February 1990.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] It was the 14th Commonwealth Games, and part of New Zealand's 1990 sesquicentennial celebrations.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Participants competed in ten sports: athletics, aquatics, badminton, boxing, cycling, gymnastics, judo, lawn bowls, shooting and weightlifting.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Judo and gymnastics are added as optional sports effectively replacing wrestling, which was dropped from the Games for the first time and rowing which had been held for the last time.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Netball and the Triathlon were demonstration events.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The event was awarded to Auckland on 27 July 1984 at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, USA.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Perth, Australia, had withdrawn from the bid contest leaving New Delhi, India, as the sole opponent to Auckland's bid.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] New Delhi lost the hosting rights to Auckland by a margin of 1 vote, which made it the closest host selection vote in the history of Commonwealth Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The primary venue was the Mount Smart Stadium, used for the opening and closing ceremonies and athletics events.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The athletes' village was located in Glen Innes at the corner of Merton Road and Morrin Road, going south towards the base of Mount Wellington.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] It consisted of 17 acres of land owned by the University of Auckland and had a central dome for the catering facilities and around 300 houses were constructed and then relocated to various suburbs for state housing after the Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The opening of the games comprised a variety of events, including the arrival of The Queen's representative Prince Edward (her youngest son), the arrival of the Queen's Baton, and many Māori ceremonial stories.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The Queens Baton was carried across the Auckland Harbour by the vessel "Ceduna".
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony itself started off with the Auckland Commonwealth Games Choir singing the *Song of Welcome*.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Upon the arrival of Prince Edward, the Māori in attendance, gave him a *Challenge of a welcome*.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This is conducted by a Māori placing a wooden baton on the ground.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] To see if the visitor comes in peace or not, the visitor must pick it up.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The New Zealand national anthem "God Defend New Zealand" was sung during a ceremonial fourteen gun salute from nearby One Tree Hill.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This was followed by the New Zealand Army Guard Commander allowing Prince Edward to inspect the guard of honour.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] After which was the introduction of the participating countries of the Commonwealth, Scotland, entering first as the hosts of the previous games, and New Zealand entering last as hosts.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] During the introduction of the countries, the choir would display the flag of the announced country with boards.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] When all the athletes finally sat down, the cultural segment ceremonies began.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The first act was the Māori women performing a "Song of Welcome" for the athletes with the use of Poi.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The Māori women then gave some of the athletes a Hongi.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Next was the Māori story of how New Zealand was formed according to legend; it a narration of how the Polynesians found their way to what was to become New Zealand, and how New Zealand was formed between Rangi and Papa, the sky father and earth mother.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The story then moved on to the coming of religion and European migration.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This was demonstrated with a formation of the Union Jack, to show the colonisation by the British.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Dame Whina Cooper then made a speech about the Treaty of Waitangi signed in 1840 that brought about peace and stability of modern New Zealand.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Introduction of the European communities was next with music and native dancing from European countries such as Italy, Poland, Greece, Netherlands, Scotland, Ireland, Austria, Wales and England, and music and native dancing also from Asian countries such as China, Sri Lanka and India.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] From here, many of the neighbouring Pacific Islanders made their entrance with the rhythmic tempo of the Pacific Island drum beat.This was to show the then complete migration of people to New Zealand.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Sir Howard Morrison then lead New Zealand in singing the folk song Tukua-a-hau.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] After Morrison, the Queen's Baton arrived at the stadium where Prince Edward announced the opening of the games which was followed by the *Athletes Pledge*.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Fireworks followed and was capped off with a night time flyover by nine A-4 Skyhawk jets of the Royal New Zealand Air Forces 75 Squadron.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The ceremony was concluded by the singing of the game's motto "This is the moment" as performers and athletes exited the stadium.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] A more relaxed affair was held for the 14th Commonwealth Games closing ceremony.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Attended by HM The Queen of New Zealand, formality and respect played their due part in the beginning with protocolar segment with the handover to the Commonwealth Games flag to the next host city, Victoria, Canada.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This was followed by a First Nations and modern Canadian dancing display.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Next, thousands of children entered the stadium with a mass skipping rope demonstration, followed by the athletes.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The Queen then made the traditional closing speech and called for all the Commonwealth's athletes to assemble in four years time in Victoria.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] As the evening wore on Dame Kiri Te Kanawa sang "Now is the Hour", a favourite New Zealand hymn, as the Royal New Zealand Air Force's A4 Skyhawks made one final swooping flyover of Mount Smart Stadium followed by fireworks.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The Queen, Duke of Edinburgh, and Prince Edward then exited the stadium standing in open top vehicles.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The mascot of the games was Goldie, representing New Zealand's national symbol the kiwi bird.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] 55 teams were represented at the 1990 Games.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This is the full table of the **medal count** of the **1990 Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] These rankings sort by the number of gold medals earned by a country.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] The number of silvers is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] This follows the system used by the IOC, IAAF and BBC.
[src:1990-commonwealth-games/1990-commonwealth-games] Figures from Commonwealth Games Foundation website.
